Rwanda Electronic Single Window (ReSW) II is building on the implementation of Phase I which was very successful and enable the Rwanda Trading Community to reduce the time and cost of moving goods out of, into and across Rwanda in general.  This phase is meant to address some of the gaps that were identified in the implementation of Phase I, improve on the benefits trade actors will get and to sustain the results that were achieved under Phase I implementation.  The key support of Phase II will be:
1.	Integration of additional agencies to the ReSW platform – that is RURA and RMB; and near features and permits from the already existing agencies in the single window ecosystem;
2.	Implementation of a Single Transaction Point that will enable submission of all data sets required to process all the required documents and processes in one form rather than the multiple forms currently in existence.

The project is designed to address operational challenges being faced by the three government entities responsible for coordinating the evacuation of cargo from Mombasa to Nairobi via the standard gauge railway line.  Some of these challenges include:
•	Lack of effective coordination between the three agencies to ensure seamless movement of cargo via the SGR line;
•	Lack of capability to provide real-time information and updates to shippers, clearing agents, transporters and the staff on the respective agencies on the status and position of cargo that is being evacuated via the SGR line;
•	Lack of solutions to provide for accurate location of cargo at the Mombasa Port and ICD-Embakasi to facilitate faster handling, mobility and clearance of cargo;
•	Lack of effective means to better manage truck traffic coming into and leaving the ICD-Embakasi facility;

This project aims at digitizing services at the Anti-Counterfeit Authority (ACA) in a bid to efficiently and effectively manage and eliminate the supply of counterfeit goods in the Kenyan market. The project entails the development of an online platform that will improve the efficiency of (among others); 

i) tracing and seizing of counterfeit goods;
ii) Disseminate relevant information and create public awareness on counterfeiting in Kenya; and
iii) Enhance coordination in the management if circulation of goods in the Kenyan market through improved information sharing among various government agencies involved in dealing with counterfeit goods

The project scope covers software solutions, hardware and implementation of change management activities. Key components include;
1.) Software solutions: Intelligent Quick Response Code System (QRC); IPR Recordal Code; Depot Enforcement and Case Management System; Counterfeit Goods Inventory Management System; Crowd-Based Counterfeit Reporting and Notification System; Integration
2.) Purchase of hardware components
